MERS-COV (12): SAUDI ARABIA
***************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 2 Apr 2018
Source: Saudi MOH 21 Mar - 1 Apr 2018 [edited]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/ccc/pressreleases/pages/default.aspx?PageIndex=1


According to the spreadsheet data I have been keeping, the most recent information available is current as of [1 Apr 2018]:

There have been a total of:
1821 newly confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection, including
735 reported fatalities [reported case fatality rate of 40.4 per cent]
1067 recoveries, and
18 currently active cases [those who have not been reflected in reports of fatalities or recoveries]

Since the last update (through 21 Mar 2018) there have been:
7 newly confirmed cases
1 newly reported death
6 newly reported recoveries
[1 of the newly reported recoveries I could not find on my newly confirmed cases spreadsheet. - Mod.MP]

Information on newly confirmed cases (7 cases):
- none of the cases were healthcare workers

1- Reported on 1 Apr 2018: A 50-year-old Saudi male from Ahad Rufaidah [`Asīr region] noted to be in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with high risk exposure history still under investigation.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-04-01-001.aspx

2- Reported on 30 Mar 2018: A 54-year-old Saudi male from Hufoof [Ash Sharqīyah - Eastern region] noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-30-001.aspx

3- Reported on 30 Mar 2018: A 5-year-old Saudi male from Hufoof [Ash Sharqīyah - Eastern region] noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-30-001.aspx

4- Reported on 24 Mar 2018: A 44-year old expat male from Hufoof [Ash Sharqīyah - Eastern region] noted to be in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-24-001.aspx

5- Reported on 24 Mar 2018: A 41-year-old Saudi female from Jeddah [Makkah region] noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a secondary case in a household contact.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-24-001.aspx

6- Reported on 23 Mar 2018: A 64-year-old expat male from Riyadh [Riyadh region] noted to be in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with high risk exposure history still under investigation.
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-23-001.aspx>

7- Reported on 21 Mar 2018: A 67-year-old Saudi male from Najran [Najran region] noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness. [reported as a recovery on 1 Apr 2018, see recovery no. 1 below - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-21-001.aspx

Information on newly reported fatalities (1 fatality):
- Reported on 31 Mar 2018: A 23-year-old Saudi male, non-healthcare worker from Riyadh [Riyadh region] with a history of pre-existing co-morbidities. [reported as a newly confirmed case on 26 Feb 2018 at which time he was noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a secondary healthcare acquired case in a patient. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-31-001.aspx

Information on newly reported recoveries (6 recoveries):
- none of the recoveries were healthcare workers

1- Reported on 1 Apr 2018: A 57-year-old Saudi male from Najran [Najran region] (see newly confirmed case no.7 above - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-04-01-001.aspx

2- Reported on 30 Mar 2018: A 60-year-old Saudi male from Riyadh [Riyadh region] with a history of pre-existing co-morbidities. [reported as a newly confirmed case on 7 Mar 2018 at which time he was noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a secondary healthcare acquired case in a patient. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-30-001.aspx

3- Reported on 30 Mar 2018: A 56yo male from Jeddah [Makkah region] with a history of pre-existing co-morbidities. [reported as a newly confirmed case on 8 Mar 2018 at which time he was noted to be in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with high risk exposure history still under investigation. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-30-001.aspx

4- Reported on 30 Mar 2018: A 21-year-old Saudi male from Buraidah [Al Qaṣīm region] with a history of pre-existing co-morbidities. [I was unable to find this individual on the spreadsheet of newly confirmed cases so no additional information was available. It is possible this case was identified during the period 17-18 Mar 2018 when there was an unaccounted for increase in case numbers using the Saudi MOH figures. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-30-001.aspx

5- Reported on 28 Mar 2018: A 42-year-old expat male from Riyadh [Riyadh region] with no history of co-morbidities. [reported as a newly confirmed case on 13 Feb 2018 at which time he was noted to be in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with high risk exposure history still under investigation. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-28-001.aspx

6- Reported on 28 Mar 2018: A 43-year-old Saudi male from Riyadh [Riyadh region] with a history of pre-existing co-morbidities. [reported as a newly confirmed case on 19 Mar 2018 at which time he was noted to be in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness. - Mod.MPP]
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2018-03-28-001.aspx

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the period since the last update (21 Mar 2018 to 1 Apr 2018) there have been 7 newly confirmed cases reported - 3 were from Hufoof in Ash Sharqīyah - Eastern Region, and 1 each from Najran - Najran region, Riyadh - Riyadh region, Jeddah - Makkah region and Ahad Rufaidah - `Asīr region. A total of 6 of the 7 cases were classified as primary cases - 4 of whom had known direct contact with camels, and 1 was in a household contact.

During the month of March 2018 there were a total of 16 newly confirmed cases, 5 deaths and 14 recoveries reported. Cases reported during March 2018, were reported from Riyadh region (5 cases), Makkah region (4 cases), Ash Sharqīyah - Eastern region (3 cases), Najran region (2 cases) and 1 each from Hail and Al Madinah regions. Of the 16, 10 were classified as primary cases, with 8 having a history of direct contact with camels, 3 were secondary household contact acquired cases and 3 were healthcare associated cases - 2 in patients and 1 in a healthcare worker.

Maps showing the locations of the newly confirmed cases, fatality and recoveries can be found at the source URLs. The HealthMap/ProMED map of Saudi Arabia can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5724114,131. - Mod.MPP]
